==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Merganser
<hw>Mer*gan"ser</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.
<ets>merg⟦aacute⟧nsar</ets>, fr. <ets>mergo</ets> a diver (L.
<ets>mergus</ets>, fr. <ets>mergere</ets> to dip, dive) +
<ets>⟦aacute⟧nsar</ets> goose, L. <ets>anser</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any bird of the genus <gen>Mergus</gen>
(<gen>Merganser</gen>), and allied genera of the subfamily
<subfam>Merginae</subfam>. They are allied to the ducks, but have a
sharply serrated bill, eat fish, and dive for food. Also called
<altname>fish duck</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The red-breasted merganser (<spn>Merganser
serrator</spn>) inhabits both hemispheres. It is called also
<altname>sawbill</altname>, <altname>harle</altname>, and
<altname>sheldrake</altname>. The American merganser (<spn>Merganser
Americanus</spn>.) and the hooded merganser (<spn>Lophodytes
cucullatus</spn>) are well-known species.</note> -- <cs><col><b>White
merganser</b></col>, <cd>the smew or white nun.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merge</ent>⟦br⟧
